1. What is Power BI, and what are its three main components?

Power BI is Microsoft’s business analytics tool for data visualization and reporting.
Main components:

Power BI Desktop – create reports and dashboards on PC.

Power BI Service (Cloud) – share and collaborate online.

Power BI Mobile – access reports via mobile devices.

2. Name two business use cases for Power BI dashboards

Real-time sales performance analysis.

Financial reporting on expenses and revenues.

3. How do you download and install Power BI Desktop?

Download it for free from Microsoft Store or from powerbi.microsoft.com, then install it on your computer.

4. What is the difference between Power BI Desktop and Power BI Service?

Desktop – build and design reports (offline).

Service – share, collaborate, and access reports online.

5. What file extension does a Power BI project use?

.pbix

6. Explain the role of Power Query in Power BI

Power Query is used to connect, clean, and transform raw data into a usable format for reporting.

7. Why would a business prefer Power BI over Excel for reporting?

Handles large datasets efficiently.

Creates interactive and dynamic dashboards.

Enables real-time connectivity and collaboration.

8. Describe one limitation of the free version of Power BI

Reports can only be viewed on the local computer; full sharing and collaboration features are not available.

9. What is a "published report" in Power BI Service?

It’s a report created in Power BI Desktop and then uploaded (published) to Power BI Service for online access and sharing.

10. How does Power BI Mobile enhance accessibility?

It allows users to view and interact with reports anytime, anywhere via smartphones and tablets.

11. Compare Power BI with Tableau—pros and cons

Power BI pros: cheaper, strong Excel integration, user-friendly.
Cons: less advanced for very complex visualizations compared to Tableau.

12. Explain how Power BI integrates with Azure services

Power BI connects directly with Azure SQL Database, Azure Data Lake, Azure Machine Learning, and other Azure services for advanced analytics.

13. What are "gateways" in Power BI, and when are they needed?

A gateway connects on-premises data sources with Power BI Service, enabling real-time data refresh and secure data transfer.

14. How would you convince a company to adopt Power BI? (ROI argument)

Faster decision-making with real-time insights.

Clear and visual data presentation.

Saves time compared to manual Excel reporting → reduces costs, increases revenue.

15. What security features does Power BI offer for sensitive data?

Row-Level Security (RLS): users only see relevant data.

Data encryption: ensures secure storage and transfer.

Azure Active Directory integration for user authentication and access control.
